%I A397561 #8 Jul 12 2026 17:01:58
%S A397561 2283,138645,27735920
%N A397561 Integers m > 1 such that gcd(m^(3*k) - 1, m! - 1) > 1 for every positive integer k.
%C A397561 Since m^3 - 1 divides m^(3*k) - 1 for every positive integer k, the defining condition is equivalent to gcd(m^3 - 1, m! - 1) > 1.
%C A397561 Moreover, gcd(2283^3 - 1, 2283! - 1) = 140929 = gcd(138645^3 - 1, 138645! - 1). If k == 0 (mod 3), then 140929 divides both gcd(2283^k - 1, 2283! - 1) and gcd(138645^k - 1, 138645! - 1).
%C A397561 If a(4) exists, then a(4) > 1005000000 (see Pessolano's answer to the MathOverflow thread in Links).
%H A397561 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/q/510302">If gcd(n^3-1, n!-1) is greater than 1, must it be equal to 140929?</a>.
%e A397561 27735920 is a term since gcd(27735920^3 - 1, 2283! - 1) = 54003043 > 1.
%Y A397561 Cf. A393224, A395115, A395171, A395944.
%K A397561 nonn,hard,bref,more,new
%O A397561 1,1
%A A397561 _Marco Ripà_ and _Aldo Roberto Pessolano_, Jun 30 2026
